Here is the full **testsmells.org 19-smell catalog** audit of `UserRepositoryIntegrationTests.cs`, with integration-test calibration applied.

---

## Summary Dashboard

| Severity | Smell Count | Affected Tests |
|----------|-------------|----------------|
| High | 3 | 3 |
| Medium | 1 | 1 |
| Low | 0 | 0 |
| **Total** | **4** | **4** |

All 19 catalog smells were evaluated. **15 smells were not detected** — see the clean-bill section at the end.

---

## Findings by Severity

### 🔴 HIGH 1 — Sleepy Test

**Catalog:** testsmells.org / Sleepy Test
**Affected:** `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` (line 87)
**Integration calibration:** Sleepy Test is **not** downgraded for integration tests. Unlike Mystery Guest or Eager Test, a hard `Thread.Sleep` is a design flaw at any scope — it causes non-deterministic failures and inflates suite runtime.

```csharp
// ❌ Current — 3-second wall-clock sleep
Thread.Sleep(3000);
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
```

**Fix — poll with a timeout:**

```csharp
// ✅ Fixed — deterministic polling with a ceiling
var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
while (!_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id))
{
    await Task.Delay(50, cts.Token);
}
Assert.IsTrue(_repository.WasNotificationSent(user.Id));
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Flaky failures in CI when the machine is under load; wasted 3 s per run even when the event fires in 10 ms.

---

### 🔴 HIGH 2 — Conditional Test Logic

**Catalog:** testsmells.org / Conditional Test Logic
**Affected:** `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` (lines 101-108)

```csharp
// ❌ Current — one branch is never exercised
if (loaded is PremiumUser premium)
{
    Assert.IsTrue(premium.DiscountRate > 0);
}
else
{
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded!.Name);
}
```

A `User` constructed with `new User(…)` will never be `PremiumUser`, so the `if` branch is **dead code** — the discount-rate assertion never runs. This is a hidden testing gap.

**Fix — split into two explicit tests:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_StandardUser_ReturnsCorrectName()
{
    _repository.Insert(new User("eve@example.com", "Eve"));
    var loaded = _repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com");

    Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
    Assert.AreEqual("Eve", loaded.Name);
}

[TestMethod]
public void GetUser_PremiumUser_HasPositiveDiscount()
{
    _repository.Insert(new PremiumUser("eve@example.com", "Eve", 0.15m));
    var loaded = (PremiumUser)_repository.GetByEmail("eve@example.com")!;

    Assert.IsTrue(loaded.DiscountRate > 0);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** The `PremiumUser` discount logic is completely untested; regressions go undetected.

---

### 🔴 HIGH 3 — Assertion-Free Test (Unknown Test)

**Catalog:** testsmells.org / Unknown Test (also called Empty Test / Assertion-Free Test)
**Affected:** `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` (lines 113-119)

```csharp
// ❌ Current — no assertion; passes even if Insert silently drops rows
for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
    _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
}
```

The method name implies a "does not throw" intent, but the framework already reports unhandled exceptions as failures — the test adds zero value beyond what the runner already does.

**Fix — assert the observable outcome:**

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void BulkInsert_PersistsAllRows()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
    {
        _repository.Insert(new User($"bulk{i}@example.com", $"Bulk User {i}"));
    }

    var users = _repository.ListAll();
    Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count);
}
```

**Risk if unfixed:** False confidence — coverage metrics look good, but Insert could silently corrupt data and this test would still pass.

---

### 🟡 MEDIUM 4 — Assertion Roulette

**Catalog:** testsmells.org / Assertion Roulette
**Affected:** `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` (lines 35-38)

```csharp
// ❌ Current — 4 assertions, no messages
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded);
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name);
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email);
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0);
```

When any of these fails, the stack trace says "`Assert.AreEqual failed`" with no hint about *which* property was wrong.

**Fix — add assertion messages:**

```csharp
Assert.IsNotNull(loaded, "User should be retrievable after insert");
Assert.AreEqual("Alice", loaded.Name, "Name should round-trip");
Assert.AreEqual("alice@example.com", loaded.Email, "Email should round-trip");
Assert.IsTrue(loaded.Id > 0, "Id should be assigned by the database");
```

**Risk if unfixed:** Slower failure triage — developers must read source to identify which property mismatched.

---

## Smells Not Detected (15 of 19 — Clean)

| # | Smell | Verdict |
|---|-------|---------|
| 2 | **Mystery Guest** | ✅ Clean — in-memory SQLite; no external files/network. *Integration-calibrated: even if a real DB were used, the `[TestCategory("Integration")]` marker makes this expected.* |
| 5 | **Eager Test** | ✅ Clean — highest distinct-method count is 3 (`Insert`, `Update`, `GetByEmail`), below the 4-method threshold. *Integration-calibrated: multi-step workflows are normal here.* |
| 6 | **Magic Number Test** | ✅ Clean — `3` in `Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count)` follows 3 explicit inserts; `10` follows 10 Task.Run iterations. Both are contextually self-documenting. |
| 7 | **Sensitive Equality** | ✅ Clean — no `ToString()` in assertions. |
| 8 | **Exception Handling** | ✅ Clean — no `try`/`catch` or `throw` in test methods. |
| 9 | **General Fixture** | ✅ Clean — `_connection` and `_repository` are used by every test. |
| 10 | **Ignored/Disabled Test** | ✅ Clean — no `[Ignore]` or `#if` guards. |
| 11 | **Duplicate Assert** | ✅ Clean — no duplicated assertion statements. |
| 12 | **Lazy Test** | ✅ Clean — each test exercises a different primary action. |
| 13 | **Constructor Initialization** | ✅ Clean — uses `[TestInitialize]`, not a constructor. |
| 14 | **Default Test** | ✅ Clean — class name is descriptive. |
| 15 | **Redundant Print** | ✅ Clean — no `Console.Write*` calls. |
| 16 | **Redundant Assertion** | ✅ Clean — no tautological assertions. |
| 17 | **Resource Optimism** | ✅ Clean — no assumed-to-exist external files. |
| 18 | **Empty Test** | ✅ Clean — no comment-only method bodies. |

---

## Well-Written Tests Worth Highlighting

- **`DeleteUser_RemovesFromDatabase`** — Clean arrange/act/assert, single concern, clear assertion.
- **`ListUsers_ReturnsAllInserted`** — Good use of `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull` alongside count check.
- **`InsertUser_ConcurrentInserts_MaintainsIntegrity`** — Properly exercises concurrency and asserts the invariant.

---

## Prioritized Remediation Plan

| Priority | Smell | Fix | Effort |
|----------|-------|-----|--------|
| 1 | **Conditional Test Logic** — `GetUser_ReturnsCorrectType` | Split into two tests; removes dead branch | ~5 min |
| 2 | **Assertion-Free Test** — `BulkInsert_RunsWithoutErrors` | Add `Assert.AreEqual(100, users.Count)` | ~1 min |
| 3 | **Sleepy Test** — `NotifyOnInsert_SendsEventAfterDelay` | Replace `Thread.Sleep` with poll loop + timeout | ~10 min |
| 4 | **Assertion Roulette** — `InsertUser_PersistsToDatabase` | Add message strings to 4 assertions | ~2 min |

**Bottom line:** 4 of 8 tests are smell-free. The 3 high-severity findings are quick fixes (items 1-2 are under 5 minutes each). After those, this is a solid integration test class.
